# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cryptographic-hardness
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] In computational complexity theory, a **computational hardness assumption** is the hypothesis that a particular problem cannot be solved efficiently (where *efficiently* typically means "in polynomial time").
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] It is not known how to prove (unconditional) hardness for essentially any useful problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Instead, computer scientists rely on reductions to formally relate the hardness of a new or complicated problem to a computational hardness assumption about a problem that is better-understood.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Computational hardness assumptions are of particular importance in cryptography.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] A major goal in cryptography is to create cryptographic primitives with provable security.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] In some cases, cryptographic protocols are found to have information theoretic security; the one-time pad is a common example.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] However, information theoretic security cannot always be achieved; in such cases, cryptographers fall back to computational security.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Roughly speaking, this means that these systems are secure *assuming that any adversaries are computationally limited*, as all adversaries are in practice.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Computational hardness assumptions are also useful for guiding algorithm designers: a simple algorithm is unlikely to refute a well-studied computational hardness assumption such as P ≠ NP.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Computer scientists have different ways of assessing which hardness assumptions are more reliable.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] We say that assumption A is *stronger* than assumption B when A implies B (and the converse is false or not known).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] In other words, even if assumption A were false, assumption B may still be true, and cryptographic protocols based on assumption B may still be safe to use.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Thus when devising cryptographic protocols, one hopes to be able to prove security using the *weakest* possible assumptions.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] An average-case assumption says that a specific problem is hard on most instances from some explicit distribution, whereas a worst-case assumption only says that the problem is hard on *some* instances.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] For a given problem, average-case hardness implies worst-case hardness, so an average-case hardness assumption is stronger than a worst-case hardness assumption for the same problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Furthermore, even for incomparable problems, an assumption like the exponential time hypothesis is often considered preferable to an average-case assumption like the planted clique conjecture.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] However, for cryptographic applications, knowing that a problem has some hard instance (the problem is hard in the worst-case) is useless because it does not provide us with a way of generating hard instances.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Fortunately, many average-case assumptions used in cryptography (including RSA, discrete log, and some lattice problems) can be based on worst-case assumptions via worst-case-to-average-case reductions.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] A desired characteristic of a computational hardness assumption is falsifiability, i.e. that if the assumption were false, then it would be possible to prove it.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] In particular, Naor (2003) introduced a formal notion of cryptographic falsifiability.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Roughly, a computational hardness assumption is said to be falsifiable if it can be formulated in terms of a challenge: an interactive protocol between an adversary and an efficient verifier, where an efficient adversary can convince the verifier to accept if and only if the assumption is false.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] There are many cryptographic hardness assumptions in use.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] This is a list of some of the most common ones, and some cryptographic protocols that use them.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Given a composite integer n , and in particular one which is the product of two large primes $n=p\cdot q$ , the integer factorization problem is to find p and q (more generally, find primes $p_{1},\dots ,p_{k}$ such that $n=\prod _{i}p_{i}$ ).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] It is a major open problem to find an algorithm for integer factorization that runs in time polynomial in the size of representation ( $\log n$ ).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The security of many cryptographic protocols rely on the assumption that integer factorization is hard (i.e. cannot be solved in polynomial time).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Cryptosystems whose security is equivalent to this assumption include Rabin signature and the Okamoto–Uchiyama cryptosystem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Many more cryptosystems rely on stronger assumptions such as RSA, residuosity problems, and phi-hiding.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Given a composite number n , exponent e and number $c:=m^{e}(\mathrm {mod} \;n)$ , the RSA problem is to find m .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The problem is conjectured to be hard, but becomes easy given the factorization of n .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] In the RSA cryptosystem, $(n,e)$ is the public key, c is the encryption of message m , and the factorization of n is the secret key used for decryption.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Important special cases include the quadratic residuosity problem and the decisional composite residuosity problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] As in the case of RSA, this problem (and its special cases) are conjectured to be hard, but become easy given the factorization of n .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] For a composite number m , it is not known how to efficiently compute its Euler's totient function $\phi (m)$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The phi-hiding assumption postulates that it is hard to compute $\phi (m)$ , and furthermore even computing any prime factors of $\phi (m)$ is hard.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] This assumption is used in the Cachin–Micali–Stadler PIR protocol.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Given elements a and b from a group G , the discrete log problem asks for an integer k such that $a=b^{k}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The discrete log problem is not known to be comparable to integer factorization, but their computational complexities are closely related.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Most cryptographic protocols related to the discrete log problem actually rely on the stronger Diffie–Hellman assumption: given group elements $g,g^{a},g^{b}$ , where g is a generator and $a,b$ are random integers, it is hard to find $g^{a\cdot b}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Examples of protocols that use this assumption include the original Diffie–Hellman key exchange, as well as the ElGamal encryption (which relies on the yet stronger Decisional Diffie–Hellman (DDH) variant).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] For cryptographic applications, one would like to construct groups $G_{1},\dots ,G_{n},G_{T}$ and a map e such that the map and the group operations on $G_{1},\dots ,G_{n},G_{T}$ can be computed efficiently, but the discrete log problem on $G_{1},\dots ,G_{n}$ is still hard.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Some applications require stronger assumptions, e.g. multilinear analogs of Diffie-Hellman assumptions.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] For the special case of $n=2$ , bilinear maps with believable security have been constructed using Weil pairing and Tate pairing.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] For $n>2$ many constructions have been proposed in recent years, but many of them have also been broken, and currently there is no consensus about a safe candidate.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The most fundamental computational problem on lattices is the shortest vector problem (SVP): given a lattice L , find the shortest non-zero vector $v\in L$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Most cryptosystems require stronger assumptions on variants of SVP, such as shortest independent vectors problem (SIVP), GapSVP, or Unique-SVP.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The most useful lattice hardness assumption in cryptography is for the learning with errors (LWE) problem: Given samples to $(x,y)$ , where $y=f(x)$ for some linear function $f(\cdot )$ , it is easy to learn $f(\cdot )$ using linear algebra.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] In the LWE problem, the input to the algorithm has errors, i.e. for each pair $y\neq f(x)$ with some small probability.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The errors are believed to make the problem intractable (for appropriate parameters); in particular, there are known worst-case to average-case reductions from variants of SVP.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] For quantum computers, factoring and discrete log problems are easy, but lattice problems are conjectured to be hard.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] This makes some lattice-based cryptosystems candidates for post-quantum cryptography.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] As well as their cryptographic applications, hardness assumptions are used in computational complexity theory to provide evidence for mathematical statements that are difficult to prove unconditionally.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] In these applications, one proves that the hardness assumption implies some desired complexity-theoretic statement, instead of proving that the statement is itself true.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The best-known assumption of this type is the assumption that P ≠ NP, but others include the exponential time hypothesis, the planted clique conjecture, and the unique games conjecture.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Many worst-case computational problems are known to be hard or even complete for some complexity class C , in particular NP-hard (but often also PSPACE-hard, PPAD-hard, etc.).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] This means that they are at least as hard as any problem in the class C .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] If a problem is C -hard (with respect to polynomial time reductions), then it cannot be solved by a polynomial-time algorithm unless the computational hardness assumption $P\neq C$ is false.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The exponential time hypothesis (ETH) is a strengthening of $P\neq NP$ hardness assumption, which conjectures that not only does the Boolean satisfiability problem (SAT) not have a polynomial time algorithm, it furthermore requires exponential time ( $2^{\Omega (n)}$ ).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] An even stronger assumption, known as the strong exponential time hypothesis (SETH) conjectures that k -SAT requires $2^{(1-\varepsilon _{k})n}$ time, where $\lim _{k\rightarrow \infty }\varepsilon _{k}=0$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] ETH, SETH, and related computational hardness assumptions allow for deducing fine-grained complexity results, e.g. results that distinguish polynomial time and quasi-polynomial time, or even $n^{1.99}$ versus $n^{2}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Such assumptions are also useful in parametrized complexity.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Some computational problems are assumed to be hard on average over a particular distribution of instances.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Another important example is Feige's Hypothesis, which is a computational hardness assumption about random instances of 3-SAT (sampled to maintain a specific ratio of clauses to variables).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Average-case computational hardness assumptions are useful for proving average-case hardness in applications like statistics, where there is a natural distribution over inputs.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Additionally, the planted clique hardness assumption has also been used to distinguish between polynomial and quasi-polynomial worst-case time complexity of other problems, similarly to the exponential time hypothesis.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] The unique label cover problem is a constraint satisfaction problem, where each constraint C involves two variables $x,y$ , and for each value of x there is a *unique* value of y that satisfies C .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Approximation problems are often known to be NP-hard assuming UGC; such problems are referred to as UG-hard.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] In particular, assuming UGC there is a semidefinite programming algorithm that achieves optimal approximation guarantees for many important problems.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Closely related to the unique label cover problem is the **small set expansion (SSE)** problem: Given a graph $G=(V,E)$ , find a small set of vertices (of size $n/\log(n)$ ) whose edge expansion is minimal.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] It is known that if SSE is hard to approximate, then so is unique label cover.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Hence, the *small set expansion hypothesis*, which postulates that SSE is hard to approximate, is a stronger (but closely related) assumption than the unique game conjecture.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Some approximation problems are known to be SSE-hard (i.e. at least as hard as approximating SSE).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] Given a set of n numbers, the 3SUM problem asks whether there is a triplet of numbers whose sum is zero.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/computational-hardness-assumption] This conjecture is useful for proving near-quadratic lower bounds for several problems, mostly from computational geometry.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] The **decisional Diffie–Hellman (DDH) assumption** is a computational hardness assumption about a certain problem involving discrete logarithms in cyclic groups.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] It is used as the basis to prove the security of many cryptographic protocols, most notably the ElGamal and Cramer–Shoup cryptosystems.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] Consider a (multiplicative) cyclic group G of order q , and with generator g .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] The DDH assumption states that, given $g^{a}$ and $g^{b}$ for uniformly and independently chosen $a,b\in \mathbb {Z} _{q}$ , the value $g^{ab}$ "looks like" a random element in G .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] Triples of the first kind are often called **DDH triplet** or **DDH tuples**.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] The DDH assumption is related to the discrete log assumption.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] If it were possible to efficiently compute discrete logs in G , then the DDH assumption would not hold in G .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] Given $(g^{a},g^{b},z)$ , one could efficiently decide whether $z=g^{ab}$ by first taking the discrete $\log _{g}$ of $g^{a}$ , and then comparing z with $(g^{b})^{a}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] DDH is considered to be a **stronger** assumption than the discrete logarithm assumption, because there are groups for which computing discrete logs is believed to be hard (and thus the DL Assumption is believed to be true), but detecting DDH tuples is easy (and thus DDH is false).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] Because of this, requiring that the DDH assumption holds in a group is believed to be a more restrictive requirement than DL.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] The DDH assumption is also related to the computational Diffie–Hellman assumption (CDH).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] If it were possible to efficiently compute $g^{ab}$ from $(g^{a},g^{b})$ , then one could easily distinguish the two probability distributions above.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] CDH is considered to be a stronger assumption than DDH because if CDH is solved, which means we can get $g^{ab}$ , the answer to DDH will become obvious.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] The problem of detecting DDH tuples is random self-reducible, meaning, roughly, that if it is hard for even a small fraction of inputs, it is hard for almost all inputs; if it is easy for even a small fraction of inputs, it is easy for almost all inputs.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] Importantly, the DDH assumption **does not hold** in the multiplicative group $\mathbb {Z} _{p}^{*}$ , where p is prime.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] This is because if g is a generator of $\mathbb {Z} _{p}^{*}$ , then the Legendre symbol of $g^{a}$ reveals if a is even or odd.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] Given $g^{a}$ , $g^{b}$ and $g^{ab}$ , one can thus efficiently compute and compare the least significant bit of a , b and $ab$ , respectively, which provides a probabilistic method to distinguish $g^{ab}$ from a random group element.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] The DDH assumption does not hold on elliptic curves over $GF(p)$ with small embedding degree (say, less than $\log ^{2}(p)$ ), a class which includes supersingular elliptic curves.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] This is because the Weil pairing or Tate pairing can be used to solve the problem directly as follows: given $P,aP,bP,cP$ on such a curve, one can compute $e(P,cP)$ and $e(aP,bP)$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] By the bilinearity of the pairings, the two expressions are equal if and only if $ab=c$ modulo the order of P .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] If the embedding degree is large (say around the size of p ) then the DDH assumption will still hold because the pairing cannot be computed.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/decisional-diffie-hellman-assumption] Even if the embedding degree is small, there are some subgroups of the curve in which the DDH assumption is believed to hold.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] In mathematics, for given real numbers a and b , the logarithm $\log _{b}(a)$ is a number x such that $b^{x}=a$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] The discrete logarithm is an analogous concept in group theory.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] In any group G , powers $b^{k}$ can be defined for all integers k , and the **discrete logarithm** $\log _{b}(a)$ is an integer k such that $b^{k}=a$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] In the special case of arithmetic modulo an integer m , the more commonly used term is **index**: One can write $k=\mathrm {ind} _{b}a\!\!\!\!{\pmod {m}}$ when $b^{k}\equiv a\!\!\!\!{\pmod {m}}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Discrete logarithms are quickly computable in a few special cases, but no efficient method is known for computing them in general.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Several cryptographic systems, including Diffie–Hellman and ElGamal, base their security on the hardness assumption that the discrete logarithm problem over carefully chosen groups has no efficient solution.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] In general, there is no subexponential time solution for black box groups.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Denote its group operation by multiplication and its identity element by 1 .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Similarly, let $b^{-k}$ denote the product of $b^{-1}$ with itself k times.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] For $k=0$ , the k th power is the identity: $b^{0}=1$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] An integer k that solves the equation $b^{k}=a$ is termed a **discrete logarithm** (or simply **logarithm**, in this context) of a to the base b .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] For any number a in this list, one can compute $\log _{10}a$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] These are instances of the discrete logarithm problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Other base-10 logarithms in the real numbers are not instances of the discrete logarithm problem, because they involve non-integer exponents.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] While integer exponents can be defined in any group using products and inverses, arbitrary real exponents, such as this 1.724276…, require other concepts such as the exponential function.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] In group-theoretic terms, the powers of 10 form a cyclic group G under multiplication, and 10 is a generator for this group.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] The discrete logarithm $\log _{10}a$ is defined for any a in G .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] A similar example holds for any non-zero real number b .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] For any element a of G , one can compute $\log _{b}a$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] One of the simplest settings for discrete logarithms is the group **Z***p*×.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] This is the group of multiplication modulo the prime p .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Its elements are non-zero congruence classes modulo p , and the group product of two elements may be obtained by ordinary integer multiplication of the elements followed by reduction modulo p .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] The k th power of one of the numbers in this group may be computed by finding its ' k th power as an integer and then finding the remainder after division by p .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] When the numbers involved are large, it is more efficient to reduce modulo p multiple times during the computation.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Regardless of the specific algorithm used, this operation is called modular exponentiation.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] The discrete logarithm is just the inverse operation.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] For example, consider the equation $3^{k}\equiv 13{\pmod {17}}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] From the example above, one solution is $k=4$ , but it is not the only solution.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Hence the equation has infinitely many solutions of the form $4+16n$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Moreover, because $16$ is the smallest positive integer m satisfying $3^{m}\equiv 1{\pmod {17}}$ , these are the only solutions.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Equivalently, the set of all possible solutions can be expressed by the constraint that $k\equiv 4{\pmod {16}}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] In the special case where b is the identity element 1 of the group G , the discrete logarithm $\log _{b}a$ is undefined for a other than 1 , and every integer k is a discrete logarithm for $a=1$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Let *C* be a Weierstrass normal form elliptic curve in the projective plane over a field *F*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Let *O* be the point at infinity on *C*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] For any points *P* and *Q* of *C*, let *P* # *Q* denote the unique third point of *C*, where the line through *P* and *Q* intersects *C*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] (If *P* = *Q*, then the line in question is the line tangent to *C* at *P*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] If *P* = *Q* = *O*, then *P* # *Q* = *O*.) Define an "addition" operation on *C* by $P+Q=(P\;\#\;Q)\;\#\;O.$ This addition operation makes *C* a commutative group with identity element *O*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] For any point *P* of *C*, let $kP=P+P+\cdots +P$ denote the sum of *k* copies of *P*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] In this context, the discrete logarithm problem is: Given points *P* and *Q*, find *k* such that $Q=kP$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] When the underlying field *F* is a finite field, this problem has cryptographic applications.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Powers obey the usual algebraic identity $b^{k+l}=b^{k}\cdot b^{l}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] defined by $f(k)=b^{k}$ is a group homomorphism from the group of integers $\mathbf {Z}$ under addition onto the subgroup H of G generated by b .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Conversely, $\log _{b}a$ does not exist for a that are not in H .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] where $\mathbf {Z} _{n}$ denotes the additive group of integers modulo n .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Can the discrete logarithm be computed in polynomial time on a classical computer?
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] The discrete logarithm problem is considered to be computationally intractable.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] For a classical (e.g., non-quantum) computer, no efficient (polynomial-time) algorithm is yet known for computing discrete logarithms in general.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] A general algorithm for computing $\log _{b}a$ in finite groups G is to raise b to larger and larger powers k until the desired a is found.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] This algorithm is sometimes called *trial multiplication*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] It requires running time linear in the size of the group G and thus exponential in the number of digits in the size of the group.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Therefore, it is an exponential-time algorithm, practical only for small groups G .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] More sophisticated algorithms exist, usually inspired by similar algorithms for integer factorization.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] These algorithms run faster than the naïve algorithm, some of them proportional to the square root of the size of the group, and thus exponential in half the number of digits in the size of the group.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] However, none of them runs in polynomial time (in the number of digits in the size of the group).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] There is an efficient quantum algorithm due to Peter Shor.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Efficient classical algorithms also exist in certain special cases.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] For example, in the group of the integers modulo p under addition, the power $b^{k}$ becomes a product $b\cdot k$ , and equality means congruence modulo p in the integers.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] The extended Euclidean algorithm finds k quickly.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] With Diffie–Hellman, a cyclic group modulo a prime p is used, allowing an efficient computation of the discrete logarithm with Pohlig–Hellman if the order of the group (being $p-1$ ) is sufficiently smooth, i.e. has no large prime factors.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] There exist groups for which computing discrete logarithms is apparently difficult.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] In some cases (e.g. large prime order subgroups of groups $\mathbf {Z} _{p}^{\times }$ ) there is not only no efficient algorithm known for the worst case, but the average-case complexity can be shown to be about as hard as the worst case using random self-reducibility.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] At the same time, the inverse problem of discrete exponentiation is not difficult (it can be computed efficiently using exponentiation by squaring, for example).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] This asymmetry is analogous to the one between integer factorization and integer multiplication.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Both asymmetries (and other possibly one-way functions) have been exploited in the construction of cryptographic systems.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] Popular choices for the group G in discrete logarithm cryptography (DLC) are the cyclic groups $\mathbf {Z} _{p}^{\times }$ (e.g.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] ElGamal encryption, Diffie–Hellman key exchange, and the Digital Signature Algorithm) and cyclic subgroups of elliptic curves over finite fields (*see* Elliptic curve cryptography).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] While there is no publicly known algorithm for solving the discrete logarithm problem in general, the first three steps of the number field sieve algorithm only depend on the group G , not on the specific elements of G whose finite $\log$ is desired.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] By precomputing these three steps for a specific group, one need only carry out the last step, which is much less computationally expensive than the first three, to obtain a specific logarithm in that group.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] It turns out that much internet traffic uses one of a handful of groups that are of order 1024 bits or less, e.g. cyclic groups with order of the Oakley primes specified in RFC 2409.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] The Logjam attack used this vulnerability to compromise a variety of internet services that allowed the use of groups whose order was a 512-bit prime number, so called export grade.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] The authors of the Logjam attack estimate that the much more difficult precomputation needed to solve the discrete log problem for a 1024-bit prime would be within the budget of a large national intelligence agency such as the U.S.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/discrete-logarithm] The Logjam authors speculate that precomputation against widely reused 1024 DH primes is behind claims in leaked NSA documents that NSA is able to break much of current cryptography.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Can integer factorization be solved in polynomial time on a classical computer?
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] In mathematics, **integer factorization** is the decomposition of a positive integer into a product of integers.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Every positive integer greater than 1 is either the product of two or more integer factors greater than 1, in which case it is a composite number, or it is not, in which case it is a prime number.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] For example, 15 is a composite number because 15 = 3 · 5, but 7 is a prime number because it cannot be decomposed in this way.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] If one of the factors is composite, it can in turn be written as a product of smaller factors, for example 60 = 3 · 20 = 3 · (5 · 4).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Continuing this process until every factor is prime is called **prime factorization**; the result is always unique up to the order of the factors by the prime factorization theorem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] To factorize a small integer n using mental or pen-and-paper arithmetic, the simplest method is trial division: checking if the number is divisible by prime numbers 2, 3, 5, and so on, up to the square root of n.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] For larger numbers, especially when using a computer, various more sophisticated factorization algorithms are more efficient.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] A prime factorization algorithm typically involves testing whether each factor is prime each time a factor is found.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] When the numbers are sufficiently large, no efficient non-quantum integer factorization algorithm is known.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] However, it has not been proven that such an algorithm does not exist.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The presumed difficulty of this problem is important for the algorithms used in cryptography such as RSA public-key encryption and the RSA digital signature.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Many areas of mathematics and computer science have been brought to bear on this problem, including elliptic curves, algebraic number theory, and quantum computing.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Not all numbers of a given length are equally hard to factor.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The hardest instances of these problems (for currently known techniques) are semiprimes, the product of two prime numbers.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Many cryptographic protocols are based on the presumed difficulty of factoring large composite integers or a related problem – for example, the RSA problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] An algorithm that efficiently factors an arbitrary integer would render RSA-based public-key cryptography insecure.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] By the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, every positive integer has a unique prime factorization.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] (By convention, 1 is the empty product.) Testing whether the integer is prime can be done in polynomial time, for example, by the AKS primality test.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] If composite, however, the polynomial time tests give no insight into how to obtain the factors.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Given a general algorithm for integer factorization, any integer can be factored into its constituent prime factors by repeated application of this algorithm.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The situation is more complicated with special-purpose factorization algorithms, whose benefits may not be realized as well or even at all with the factors produced during decomposition.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] For example, if *n* = 171 × *p* × *q* where *p* < *q* are very large primes, trial division will quickly produce the factors 3 and 19 but will take *p* divisions to find the next factor.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] While these are easily recognized as composite and prime respectively, Fermat's method will take much longer to factor the composite number because the starting value of ⌈√18848997157⌉ = 137292 for *a* is a factor of 10 from 1372933.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Among the *b*-bit numbers, the most difficult to factor in practice using existing algorithms are those semiprimes whose factors are of similar size.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] For this reason, these are the integers used in cryptographic applications.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] In 2019, a 240-digit (795-bit) number (RSA-240) was factored by a team of researchers including Paul Zimmermann, utilizing approximately 900 core-years of computing power.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] These researchers estimated that a 1024-bit RSA modulus would take about 500 times as long.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The largest such semiprime yet factored was RSA-250, an 829-bit number with 250 decimal digits, in February 2020.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The total computation time was roughly 2700 core-years of computing using Intel Xeon Gold 6130 at 2.1 GHz.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Like all recent factorization records, this factorization was completed with a highly optimized implementation of the general number field sieve run on hundreds of machines.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] No algorithm has been published that can factor all integers in polynomial time, that is, that can factor a *b*-bit number *n* in time O(*b**k*) for some constant *k*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Neither the existence nor non-existence of such algorithms has been proved, but it is generally suspected that they do not exist.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] There are published algorithms that are faster than O((1 + *ε*)*b*) for all positive *ε*, that is, sub-exponential.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] For current computers, GNFS is the best published algorithm for large *n* (more than about 400 bits).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] For a quantum computer, however, Peter Shor discovered an algorithm in 1994 that solves it in polynomial time.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Shor's algorithm takes only O(*b*3) time and O(*b*) space on *b*-bit number inputs.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] In 2001, Shor's algorithm was implemented for the first time, by using NMR techniques on molecules that provide seven qubits.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] In order to talk about complexity classes such as P, NP, and co-NP, the problem has to be stated as a decision problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] It is known to be in both NP and co-NP, meaning that both "yes" and "no" answers can be verified in polynomial time.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] An answer of "yes" can be certified by exhibiting a factorization *n* = *d*(⁠*n*/*d*⁠) with *d* ≤ *k*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] An answer of "no" can be certified by exhibiting the factorization of *n* into distinct primes, all larger than *k*; one can verify their primality using the AKS primality test, and then multiply them to obtain *n*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The fundamental theorem of arithmetic guarantees that there is only one possible string of increasing primes that will be accepted, which shows that the problem is in both UP and co-UP.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] It is known to be in BQP because of Shor's algorithm.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The problem is suspected to be outside all three of the complexity classes P, NP-complete, and co-NP-complete.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] It is therefore a candidate for the NP-intermediate complexity class.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] In contrast, the decision problem "Is *n* a composite number?" (or equivalently: "Is *n* a prime number?") appears to be much easier than the problem of specifying factors of *n*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The composite/prime problem can be solved in polynomial time (in the number *b* of digits of *n*) with the AKS primality test.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] In addition, there are several probabilistic algorithms that can test primality very quickly in practice if one is willing to accept a vanishingly small possibility of error.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The ease of primality testing is a crucial part of the RSA algorithm, as it is necessary to find large prime numbers to start with.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] A special-purpose factoring algorithm's running time depends on the properties of the number to be factored or on one of its unknown factors: size, special form, etc.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The parameters which determine the running time vary among algorithms.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] An important subclass of special-purpose factoring algorithms is the *Category 1* or *First Category* algorithms, whose running time depends on the size of smallest prime factor.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Given an integer of unknown form, these methods are usually applied before general-purpose methods to remove small factors.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] For example, naive trial division is a Category 1 algorithm.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] A general-purpose factoring algorithm, also known as a *Category 2*, *Second Category*, or *Kraitchik* *family* algorithm, has a running time which depends solely on the size of the integer to be factored.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] This is the type of algorithm used to factor RSA numbers.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Most general-purpose factoring algorithms are based on the congruence of squares method.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Some examples of those algorithms are the elliptic curve method and the quadratic sieve.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Another such algorithm is the **class group relations method** proposed by Schnorr, Seysen, and Lenstra, which they proved only assuming the unproved generalized Riemann hypothesis.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The Schnorr–Seysen–Lenstra probabilistic algorithm has been rigorously proven by Lenstra and Pomerance to have expected running time *Ln*[⁠1/2⁠, 1+*o*(1)] by replacing the GRH assumption with the use of multipliers.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The algorithm uses the class group of positive binary quadratic forms of discriminant Δ denoted by *G*Δ.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] *G*Δ is the set of triples of integers (*a*, *b*, *c*) in which those integers are relative prime.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Given an integer n that will be factored, where n is an odd positive integer greater than a certain constant.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] In this factoring algorithm the discriminant Δ is chosen as a multiple of n, Δ = −*dn*, where d is some positive multiplier.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The algorithm expects that for one d there exist enough smooth forms in *G*Δ.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Lenstra and Pomerance show that the choice of d can be restricted to a small set to guarantee the smoothness result.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Denote by *P*Δ the set of all primes q with Kronecker symbol (⁠Δ/*q*⁠) = 1.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] By constructing a set of generators of *G*Δ and prime forms *f**q* of *G*Δ with q in *P*Δ a sequence of relations between the set of generators and *f**q* are produced.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The size of q can be bounded by *c*0(log|Δ|)2 for some constant *c*0.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The relation that will be used is a relation between the product of powers that is equal to the neutral element of *G*Δ.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] These relations will be used to construct a so-called ambiguous form of *G*Δ, which is an element of *G*Δ of order dividing 2.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] By calculating the corresponding factorization of Δ and by taking a gcd, this ambiguous form provides the complete prime factorization of n.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Let *f**q* be a random prime form of *G*Δ with (⁠Δ/*q*⁠) = 1.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] Construct an ambiguous form (*a*, *b*, *c*) that is an element *f* ∈ *G*Δ of order dividing 2 to obtain a coprime factorization of the largest odd divisor of Δ in which Δ = −4*ac* or Δ = *a*(*a* − 4*c*) or Δ = (*b* − 2*a*)(*b* + 2*a*).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] If the ambiguous form provides a factorization of n then stop, otherwise find another ambiguous form until the factorization of n is found.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] In order to prevent useless ambiguous forms from generating, build up the 2-Sylow group Sll2(Δ) of *G*(Δ).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] To obtain an algorithm for factoring any positive integer, it is necessary to add a few steps to this algorithm such as trial division, and the Jacobi sum test.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/integer-factorization] The algorithm as stated is a probabilistic algorithm as it makes random choices.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In computer science, **lattice problems** are a class of optimization problems related to mathematical objects called *lattices*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The conjectured intractability of such problems is central to the construction of secure lattice-based cryptosystems: lattice problems are an example of NP-hard problems which have been shown to be average-case hard, providing a test case for the security of cryptographic algorithms.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In addition, some lattice problems which are worst-case hard can be used as a basis for extremely secure cryptographic schemes.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The use of worst-case hardness in such schemes makes them among the very few schemes that are very likely secure even against quantum computers.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] For applications in such cryptosystems, lattices over vector spaces (often $\mathbb {Q} ^{n}$ ) or free modules (often $\mathbb {Z} ^{n}$ ) are generally considered.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] For all the problems below, assume that we are given (in addition to other more specific inputs) a basis for the vector space *V* and a norm *N*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The norm usually considered is the Euclidean norm *L*2.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] However, other norms (such as *L**p*) are also considered and show up in a variety of results.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In the SVP, a basis of a vector space *V* and a norm *N* (often *L*2) are given for a lattice *L* and one must find the shortest non-zero vector in *V*, as measured by *N*, in *L*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In other words, the algorithm should output a non-zero vector *v* such that ⁠ $\|v\|_{N}=\lambda (L)$ ⁠.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In the following, the size of the problem is specified by *n*, the dimension of the vector space *V*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In the γ-approximation version SVPγ, one must find a non-zero lattice vector of length at most $\gamma \cdot \lambda (L)$ for given ⁠ $\gamma \geq 1$ ⁠.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The exact version of the problem is only known to be NP-hard for randomized reductions.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] By contrast, the corresponding problem with respect to the uniform norm is known to be NP-hard.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The former class of algorithms most notably includes lattice enumeration and random sampling reduction, while the latter includes lattice sieving, computing the Voronoi cell of the lattice, and discrete Gaussian sampling.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] An open problem is whether algorithms for solving exact SVP exist running in single exponential time ( $2^{O(n)}$ ) and requiring memory scaling polynomially in the lattice dimension.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] To solve the γ-approximation version SVPγ for $\gamma >1$ for the Euclidean norm, the best known approaches are based on using lattice basis reduction.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] For large ⁠ $\gamma =2^{\Omega (n)}$ ⁠, the Lenstra–Lenstra–Lovász (LLL) algorithm can find a solution in time polynomial in the lattice dimension.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] For small $\gamma$ , larger $\beta$ are needed to find sufficiently short lattice vectors, and the algorithm takes longer to find a solution.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The BKZ algorithm internally uses an exact SVP algorithm as a subroutine (running in lattices of dimension at most $\beta$ ), and its overall complexity is closely related to the costs of these SVP calls in dimension ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The problem GapSVPβ consists of distinguishing between the instances of SVP in which the length of the shortest vector is at most 1 or larger than ⁠ $\beta$ ⁠, where $\beta$ can be a fixed function of the dimension of the lattice ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Given a basis for the lattice, the algorithm must decide whether $\lambda (L)\leq 1$ or ⁠ $\lambda (L)>\beta$ ⁠.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Like other promise problems, the algorithm is allowed to err on all other cases.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Yet another version of the problem is GapSVPζ,γ for some functions ζ and γ.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The input to the algorithm is a basis B and a number d .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] It is assured that all the vectors in the Gram–Schmidt orthogonalization are of length at least 1, and that $\lambda (L(B))\leq \zeta (n)$ and that ⁠ $1\leq d\leq \zeta (n)/\gamma (n)$ ⁠, where n is the dimension.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The algorithm must accept if ⁠ $\lambda (L(B))\leq d$ ⁠, and reject if ⁠ $\lambda (L(B))\geq \gamma (n)\cdot d$ ⁠.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] For large $\zeta$ (i.e. ⁠ $\zeta (n)>2^{n/2}$ ⁠), the problem is equivalent to GapSVPγ because a preprocessing done using the LLL algorithm makes the second condition (and hence, ⁠ $\zeta$ ⁠) redundant.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In CVP, a basis of a vector space *V* and a metric *M* (often *L*2) are given for a lattice *L*, as well as a vector *v* in *V* but not necessarily in *L*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] It is desired to find the vector in *L* closest to *v* (as measured by *M*).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In the $\gamma$ -approximation version CVPγ, one must find a lattice vector at distance at most $\gamma$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The closest vector problem is a generalization of the shortest vector problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] It is easy to show that given an oracle for CVPγ (defined below), one can solve SVPγ by making some queries to the oracle.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The naive method to find the shortest vector by calling the CVPγ oracle to find the closest vector to 0 does not work because 0 is itself a lattice vector and the algorithm could potentially output 0.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The reduction from SVPγ to CVPγ is as follows: Suppose that the input to the SVPγ is the basis for lattice $B=[b_{1},b_{2},\ldots ,b_{n}]$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The claim is that the shortest vector in the set $\{x_{i}-b_{i}\}$ is the shortest vector in the given lattice.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Goldreich et al. showed that any hardness of SVP implies the same hardness for CVP.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Using PCP tools, Arora et al. showed that CVP is hard to approximate within factor $2^{\log ^{1-\epsilon }(n)}$ unless $\operatorname {NP} \subseteq \operatorname {DTIME} (2^{\operatorname {poly} (\log n)})$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Dinur et al. strengthened this by giving a NP-hardness result with $\epsilon =(\log \log n)^{c}$ for $c<1/2$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Algorithms for CVP, especially the Fincke and Pohst variant, have been used for data detection in multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) wireless communication systems (for coded and uncoded signals).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In this context it is called *sphere decoding* due to the radius used internal to many CVP solutions.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] It has been applied in the field of the integer ambiguity resolution of carrier-phase GNSS (GPS).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] It is called the *LAMBDA method* in that field.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In the same field, the general CVP problem is referred to as *Integer Least Squares*.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] This problem is similar to the GapSVP problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The opposite condition is that the closest lattice vector is at a distance $1<\lambda (L)\leq \beta$ , hence the name *Gap*CVP.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The problem is trivially contained in NP for any approximation factor.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Schnorr, in 1987, showed that deterministic polynomial time algorithms can solve the problem for $\beta =2^{O(n(\log \log n)^{2}/\log n)}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Ajtai et al. showed that probabilistic algorithms can achieve a slightly better approximation factor of $\beta =2^{O(n\log \log n/\log n)}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In 1993, Banaszczyk showed that GapCVPn is in ${\mathsf {NP\cap coNP}}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In 2000, Goldreich and Goldwasser showed that $\beta ={\sqrt {n/\log n}}$ puts the problem in both NP and coAM.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In 2005, Aharonov and Regev showed that for some constant c , the problem with $\beta =c{\sqrt {n}}$ is in ${\mathsf {NP\cap coNP}}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] For lower bounds, Dinur et al. showed in 1998 that the problem is NP-hard for $\beta =n^{o(1/\log {\log {n}})}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Given a lattice L of dimension *n*, the algorithm must output *n* linearly independent $v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n}$ so that $\max \|v_{i}\|\leq \max _{B}\|b_{i}\|$ , where the right-hand side considers all bases $B=\{b_{1},\ldots ,b_{n}\}$ of the lattice.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In the $\gamma$ -approximate version, given a lattice L with dimension *n*, one must find *n* linearly independent vectors $v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n}$ of length ⁠ $\max \|v_{i}\|\leq \gamma \lambda _{n}(L)$ ⁠, where $\lambda _{n}(L)$ is the ⁠ n ⁠th successive minimum of ⁠ L ⁠.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Given a vector such that its distance from the lattice is at most $\lambda (L)/2$ , the algorithm must output the closest lattice vector to it.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Given a basis for the lattice, the algorithm must find the largest distance (or in some versions, its approximation) from any vector to the lattice.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Many problems become easier if the input basis consists of short vectors.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] An algorithm that solves the Shortest Basis Problem (SBP) must, given a lattice basis ⁠ B ⁠, output an equivalent basis $B'$ such that the length of the longest vector in $B'$ is as short as possible.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The approximation version SBPγ problem consist of finding a basis whose longest vector is at most $\gamma$ times longer than the longest vector in the shortest basis.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Average-case hardness of problems forms a basis for proofs-of-security for most cryptographic schemes.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] However, experimental evidence suggests that most NP-hard problems lack this property: they are probably only worst case hard.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Many lattice problems have been conjectured or proven to be average-case hard, making them an attractive class of problems to base cryptographic schemes on.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Moreover, worst-case hardness of some lattice problems have been used to create secure cryptographic schemes.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The above lattice problems are easy to solve if the algorithm is provided with a "good" basis.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Lattice reduction algorithms aim, given a basis for a lattice, to output a new basis consisting of relatively short, nearly orthogonal vectors.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The Lenstra–Lenstra–Lovász lattice basis reduction algorithm (LLL) was an early efficient algorithm for this problem which could output an almost reduced lattice basis in polynomial time.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] This algorithm and its further refinements were used to break several cryptographic schemes, establishing its status as a very important tool in cryptanalysis.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] The success of LLL on experimental data led to a belief that lattice reduction might be an easy problem in practice; however, this belief was challenged in the late 1990s, when several new results on the hardness of lattice problems were obtained, starting with the result of Ajtai.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] In his seminal papers, Ajtai showed that the SVP problem was NP-hard and discovered some connections between the worst-case complexity and average-case complexity of some lattice problems.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/lattice-problem] Building on these results, Ajtai and Dwork created a public-key cryptosystem whose security could be proven using only the worst case hardness of a certain version of SVP, thus making it the first result to have used worst-case hardness to create secure systems.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] In cryptography, **learning with errors** (**LWE**) is a mathematical problem that is widely used to create secure encryption algorithms.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] It is based on the idea of representing secret information as a set of equations with errors.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] In other words, LWE is a way to hide the value of a secret by introducing noise to it.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] In more technical terms, it refers to the computational problem of inferring a linear n -ary function f over a finite ring from given samples $y_{i}=f(\mathbf {x} _{i})$ some of which may be erroneous.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The LWE problem is conjectured to be hard to solve, and thus to be useful in cryptography.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] More precisely, the LWE problem is defined as follows.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Let $\mathbb {Z} _{q}$ denote the ring of integers modulo q and let $\mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}$ denote the set of n -vectors over $\mathbb {Z} _{q}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Furthermore, the deviation from the equality is according to some known noise model.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The problem calls for finding the function f , or some close approximation thereof, with high probability.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The LWE problem was introduced by Oded Regev in 2005 (who won the 2018 Gödel Prize for this work); it is a generalization of the parity learning problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Regev showed that the LWE problem is as hard to solve as several worst-case lattice problems.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Subsequently, the LWE problem has been used as a hardness assumption to create public-key cryptosystems, such as the ring learning with errors key exchange by Peikert.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Denote by $\mathbb {T} =\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Z}$ the additive group on reals modulo one.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Let $\mathbf {s} \in \mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}$ be a fixed vector.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Let $\phi$ be a fixed probability distribution over $\mathbb {T}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Denote by $A_{\mathbf {s} ,\phi }$ the distribution on $\mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}\times \mathbb {T}$ obtained as follows.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The **learning with errors problem** $\mathrm {LWE} _{q,\phi }$ is to find $\mathbf {s} \in \mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}$ , given access to polynomially many samples of choice from $A_{\mathbf {s} ,\phi }$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The **LWE** problem described above is the *search* version of the problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] In the *decision* version (**DLWE**), the goal is to distinguish between noisy inner products and uniformly random samples from $\mathbb {Z} _{q}^{n}\times \mathbb {T}$ (practically, some discretized version of it).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Regev showed that the *decision* and *search* versions are equivalent when q is a prime bounded by some polynomial in n .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Intuitively, if we have a procedure for the search problem, the decision version can be solved easily: just feed the input samples for the decision problem to the solver for the search problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] If the solver returns a candidate $\mathbf {s}$ , for all i , calculate $\{\langle \mathbf {a} _{i},\mathbf {s} \rangle -\mathbf {b} _{i}\}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] If the samples are from an LWE distribution, then the results of this calculation will be distributed according $\chi$ , but if the samples are uniformly random, these quantities will be distributed uniformly as well.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] For the other direction, given a solver for the decision problem, the search version can be solved as follows: Recover $\mathbf {s}$ one coordinate at a time.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] To obtain the first coordinate, $\mathbf {s} _{1}$ , make a guess $k\in \mathbb {Z} _{q}$ , and do the following.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Choose a number $r\in \mathbb {Z} _{q}$ uniformly at random.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Send the transformed samples to the decision solver.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] If the guess k was correct, the transformation takes the distribution $A_{\mathbf {s} ,\chi }$ to itself, and otherwise, since q is prime, it takes it to the uniform distribution.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] So, given a polynomial-time solver for the decision problem that errs with very small probability, since q is bounded by some polynomial in n , it only takes polynomial time to guess every possible value for k and use the solver to see which one is correct.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] After obtaining $\mathbf {s} _{1}$ , we follow an analogous procedure for each other coordinate $\mathbf {s} _{j}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Namely, we transform our $\mathbf {b} _{i}$ samples the same way, and transform our $\mathbf {a} _{i}$ samples by calculating $\mathbf {a} _{i}+(0,\ldots ,r,\ldots ,0)$ , where the r is in the $j^{\text{th}}$ coordinate.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Peikert showed that this reduction, with a small modification, works for any q that is a product of distinct, small (polynomial in n ) primes.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The main idea is if $q=q_{1}q_{2}\cdots q_{t}$ , for each $q_{\ell }$ , guess and check to see if $\mathbf {s} _{j}$ is congruent to $0\mod q_{\ell }$ , and then use the Chinese remainder theorem to recover $\mathbf {s} _{j}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Regev showed the random self-reducibility of the **LWE** and **DLWE** problems for arbitrary q and $\chi$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Then there would be some distinguisher ${\mathcal {A}}$ , who, given samples $\{(\mathbf {a} _{i},\mathbf {b} _{i})\}$ , could tell whether they were uniformly random or from $A_{\mathbf {s} ',\chi }$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Thus, no such ${\mathcal {S}}$ can exist, meaning **LWE** and **DLWE** are (up to a polynomial factor) as hard in the average case as they are in the worst case.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Let $D_{L,r}$ denote the discrete Gaussian distribution on L of width r for a lattice L and real $r>0$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The probability of each $x\in L$ is proportional to $\rho _{r}(x)$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The *discrete Gaussian sampling problem* (DGS) is defined as follows: An instance of $DGS_{\phi }$ is given by an n -dimensional lattice L and a number $r\geq \phi (L)$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The goal is to output a sample from $D_{L,r}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Regev shows that there is a reduction from $\operatorname {GapSVP} _{100{\sqrt {n}}\gamma (n)}$ to $DGS_{{\sqrt {n}}\gamma (n)/\lambda (L^{*})}$ for any function $\gamma (n)\geq 1$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Regev then shows that there exists an efficient quantum algorithm for $DGS_{{\sqrt {2n}}\eta _{\varepsilon }(L)/\alpha }$ given access to an oracle for $\mathrm {LWE} _{q,\Psi _{\alpha }}$ for integer q and $\alpha \in (0,1)$ such that $\alpha q>2{\sqrt {n}}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Although the proof of this assertion works for any q , for creating a cryptosystem, the modulus q has to be polynomial in n .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The **LWE** problem serves as a versatile problem used in construction of several cryptosystems.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] In 2005, Regev showed that the decision version of LWE is hard assuming quantum hardness of the lattice problems $\mathrm {GapSVP} _{\gamma }$ (for $\gamma$ as above) and $\mathrm {SIVP} _{t}$ with $t=O(n/\alpha )$ ).
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] In 2009, Peikert proved a similar result assuming only the classical hardness of the related problem $\mathrm {GapSVP} _{\zeta ,\gamma }$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The disadvantage of Peikert's result is that it bases itself on a non-standard version of an easier (when compared to SIVP) problem GapSVP.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Regev proposed a public-key cryptosystem based on the hardness of the **LWE** problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The cryptosystem as well as the proof of security and correctness are completely classical.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The system is characterized by $m,q$ and a probability distribution $\chi$ on $\mathbb {T}$ .
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The proof of correctness follows from choice of parameters and some probability analysis.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] Peikert proposed a system that is secure even against any chosen-ciphertext attack.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The idea of using LWE and Ring LWE for key exchange was proposed and filed at the University of Cincinnati in 2011 by Jintai Ding.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The idea comes from the associativity of matrix multiplications, and the errors are used to provide the security.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The paper appeared in 2012 after a provisional patent application was filed in 2012.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The security of the protocol is proven based on the hardness of solving the LWE problem.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] In 2014, Peikert presented a key-transport scheme following the same basic idea of Ding's, where the new idea of sending an additional 1-bit signal for rounding in Ding's construction is also used.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] The "new hope" implementation selected for Google's post-quantum experiment, uses Peikert's scheme with variation in the error distribution.
[src:cryptographic-hardness/learning-with-errors] A RLWE version of the classic Feige–Fiat–Shamir Identification protocol was created and converted to a digital signature in 2011 by Lyubashevsky.
